    <name>
      <text>Applying mixed laws of indices using bundles of paper</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Watamuu Comprehensive School</strong> is buying blocks of writing paper for Grade \(10\) learners. Each block contains \({@base@}^{@a@}\) sheets of paper. The school buys \({@base@}^{@b@}\) blocks. The blocks are then taken apart and its sheets are packed into bundles to be given to the students, each bundle containing \({@base@}^{@c@}\) sheets.</p>

<p>
By applying Laws of indices, how many bundles of sheets are formed?
Write your answer as a <strong>single power</strong>, in index form.
</p>

<p>
[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]
</p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<h3>Worked Solution</h3>

<p>
First, find the total number of sheets:
</p>

<p>
\[
{@base@}^{@a@} \times {@base@}^{@b@}
= {@base@}^{@a + b@}
\]
</p>

<p>
Next, divide by the number of sheets in each bundle:
</p>

<p>
\[
\frac{{@base@}^{@a + b@}}{{@base@}^{@c@}}
= {@base@}^{{@a + b@} - {@c@}}
\]
</p>

<p>
Therefore, the number of bundles formed is:
</p>

<p>
\[
\boxed{{@base@}^{@exp_total@}}
\]
</p>]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
